

The proposed research focuses on improving small object detection in UAV aerial imagery by enhancing the UAVDet architecture through the integration 
of a Tiny Object Aware Attention Module (TOAM). The objective is to improve feature representation and detection accuracy while maintaining computational efficiency.

The overall workflow begins with UAV aerial images obtained from publicly available datasets such as VisDrone, UAVDT, and DroneVehicle. 
These datasets contain various object categories including cars, trucks, buses, bicycles, motorcycles, and pedestrians captured from aerial viewpoints.

In the first stage, input images are preprocessed through resizing, normalization, and augmentation techniques. 
Data augmentation methods such as flipping, rotation, scaling, and brightness adjustment are applied to improve model generalization.

The preprocessed images are then passed to the CNN backbone of UAVDet. The CNN component extracts low-level 
spatial features such as edges, textures, shapes, and object boundaries. These local features provide detailed visual information necessary for object recognition.

Next, the extracted features are processed through the Cross Stage Partial Mamba Block (CSPMB). 
The Vision Mamba component captures long-range dependencies and global contextual information, allowing the network to understand relationships among distant image regions.

To further improve small object representation, the proposed Tiny Object Aware Attention Module (TOAM) is inserted between the CNN and Mamba stages. 
The TOAM module analyzes feature maps and assigns higher weights to regions likely to contain small objects while suppressing irrelevant background information.

The enhanced feature maps are subsequently forwarded to the Tiny Feature Pyramid Network (TFPN). 
TFPN performs multiscale feature fusion by combining low-level and high-level features. This process preserves critical information required for detecting objects of varying sizes, especially tiny objects.

The fused feature representations are then sent to the detection head. The detection head predicts object categories, 
confidence scores, and bounding box coordinates for each detected object.

The model is trained using supervised learning techniques with annotated ground-truth labels available in the selected datasets.
Performance evaluation is conducted using standard object detection metrics including Precision, Recall, F1-Score, mAP50, mAP50-95, and Average Precision for Small Objects (APS).

Experimental results obtained from the proposed TOAM-UAVDet framework will be compared against the original UAVDet architecture and 
other state-of-the-art methods. Improvements in detection accuracy, small object recognition, and computational efficiency will be analyzed.

The proposed methodology is expected to enhance the capability of UAV-based object detection systems by enabling more accurate identification of small objects 
in complex aerial environments. This improvement can contribute to applications such as traffic monitoring, surveillance, disaster response, smart transportation systems, and public safety management.
